that I have two beauties in my life. On one side, I have all what traditional medicine teaches us and which to me seem coherent with the basic sciences; it seems to me that when I look into a book, more often than not I find the questions and the answers from the theory of bones automatically coming directly into my own understanding without any hard repetition. With the same ease, I understand the theories of pulses, characteristics of smell for the most part, the characteristics of the tongue and many of the theories of our external or internal environment. In other words, these two sides of science and of traditional medicine irresistibly appeal to my mind.

On the other side, I have the Western medicine that seems to give answers to biological problems by artificially modifying the chemical composition of our bodies by dosage—often in its pharmacology—and limiting the pathology to a single diagnosis. To me, the other hypothesis of western medicine seems to me only a retaliatory hypothesis that is directed to masking the pathologies they find favor with and that do not really cure them. But in practice, when I pick a scrip- ture to review, the research work that I do only confirms what I have always known- that it’s not the prescriptions themselves but the natural and fascinating practice of traditional methods and theories that lead to the cure.
